A '''Detaining Power''' is the country, state, government, or any other jurisdiction which detains, holds, or incarcerates those who are alleged to have committed an offence against this [[jurisdiction]] or others (which for whatever reason have not been or will be proven not to be fit to process the detainees in question).  In short, anyone who prevents someone from leaving a country or state and may have lawfully arrested and held such persons for a length of time may be referred to as a Detaining Power.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ihl-databases.icrc.org/ihl/INTRO/375?OpenDocument|title=Treaties, States parties, and Commentaries - Geneva Convention (III) on Prisoners of War, 1949|website=ihl-databases.icrc.org|language=en-us|access-date=2017-01-17}}</ref>

For legal purposes, it is a condition of the 3rd drafting of the [[Geneva convention|Geneva Agreement]] that a detainee may request that their crimes be proven to justify their incarceration.{{citation needed|date=January 2017}}

At time of submission the [[Quirin]] case and the [[Guantanamo Bay detainment camp|Guantanamo Bay]] trials are examples of highly disputed Detaining Power in the US and under the US jurisdiction.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-DR-1TjtUcEC&lpg=PA144&ots=AAwRr5-Z3_&dq=%22detaining%20power%22&pg=PP1#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=George W. Bush, War Criminal?: The Bush Administration's Liability for 269 War Crimes|last=Haas|first=Michael|date=2009-01-01|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9780313364990|language=en}}</ref>

