The '''Uniform Interstate Depositions and Discovery Act''' (UIDDA) is a [[Uniform Act | model statute]] adopted by a majority of U.S. states to establish a uniform process for obtaining [[Deposition (law) | depositions]] and [[Discovery (law) | discovery]] in concert with other participating states. In 2007 the [[Uniform Law Commission]] (then primarily referred to as the National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Laws) promulgated, and recommended all states enact, the UIDDA. To identify at which stage of enactment the various states and territories are, ULC maintains an [http://uniformlaws.org/LegislativeMap.aspx?title=Interstate%20Depositions%20and%20Discovery%20Act up-to-date map].<ref>{{cite web |author=National Conference of Commissioners on Uniform State Laws |date=27 July 2007 |title=Uniform Depositions and Discovery Act |work=116th Annual Conference of NCCUSL |url=http://www.uniformlaws.org/Act.aspx?title=Interstate%20Depositions%20and%20Discovery%20Act |accessdate=11 June 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Hinote |first=Melissa |title=Issuing Out-of-State Subpoenas |publisher=The National Association of Legal Professionals |date=2 September 2010 |url=http://www.nals.org/?p=1621 |accessdate=14 October 2012 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Pollack |first=Joshua |author2=Wright, Joseph |title=Preparing for the UIDDA’s New Rules for Foreign Depositions |work=Los Angeles Lawyer |publisher=Los Angeles County Bar Association |date=December 2008 |url=http://www.lacba.org/Files/LAL/Vol31No9/2544.pdf |accessdate=14 October 2012 }}</ref>
